<br>
You’re supposed to think of The Pledge as an overall statement of unity, an oath that makes you part of something when you place your right hand over your heart and state those words every morning.<br>
<br>
I could see a few reasons to change the Pledge of Allegiance, too bad none of them actually exist. Maybe if it said, “…one nation under God, or get the fvck out!” or “…one nation under God, except for Negros!” but it doesn’t. The Pledge isn’t, and never was, inflammatory, derogatory or any other “ory” word. It’s non-denominational in it’s reference to a general “God” and not a Christian God or Zeus or Allah or Krishna.<br>
<br>
Seems some people feel slighted that a person or group in history put their views before everyone else’s, not everyone believes in God and therefore the statement should be removed. Sounds like a valid argument except… what about all the people who DO believe in God? I mean, it’s not like you can expect America to be the land of agnosticism. People kicked out of England for wanting religious freedom founded the US.<br>
<br>
You want “…under God” removed because it pushes it’s beliefs onto you, aren’t you then pushing your beliefs, or lack there of, onto everyone else? Hope you don’t belong to a <a href=http://www.dictionary.com/search?q=ymca>Y.M.C.A</a>, that stands for Young Men’s Christian Association, which, in Gloriana’s case, would be a double whammy(not a guy OR religious). But, once again, they won’t deny a person access if they aren’t a male or Christian. We should probably hang those damn elitists anyway!<br>
<br>
People should think of the Pledge as a one hit wonder, something you might not be able to sing in its entirety 10-20-40 years from now. But, much like the chorus of a popular song of long years past, you will always remember the important part… “…with Liberty and Justice for all.” If the government ever comes up short on those two words, I’ll stand right beside you to fight the power, until then – fvck off. <p><b>Vendrix</b><br>
