<br>
Nice research on the history of the pledge.  I was unaware of the origins or the changes since it was originally written.  Thank you for sharing. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I personally take great pride in saying the &quot;under God&quot; version of the pledge, but completely respect the right of those who desire to give their version without those two words.<br>
<br>
I used to have to say a school prayer when I was in elementary school (separate from the pledge, which I've always enjoyed), and would get in trouble for not saying it.  I was living in the Bible belt at the time.  I used to just skip the part about Jesus Christ, as he is not central to my own faith.  It was easier than trying to fight the majority, and I was only eight or nine years old at the time.  (Civil disobedience wasn't high on my priority list.  Playing kickball was. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )  It always rankled that I couldn't say my own prayer (back then, everyone said the same thing regardless) and I have empathy for those of polytheistic religions or without faith that have heartburn over saying &quot;under God&quot;.  <br>
<br>
While I think the lawsuit wasted a TON of money that could have been spent on more worthy causes, it doesn't really matter now after the fact.  Tolerance is the buzzword of the times, and I definitely prefer us leaning in that direction over intolerance. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As a side note, when you take the Oath of Enlistment &amp; the Commissioning oath in the US military, it used to be standard to say &quot;I swear&quot; (to God) and &quot;so help me God&quot;.<br>
<br>
Those phrases are now optional (and have been that way for several years).  Instead, you may say &quot;I affirm&quot; and completely skip the second phrase if that is your desire.<br>
<br>
