<br>
Well, since we(Americans) learn the Pledge somewhere around age 6, I think we can make up our own minds about who this “God” is, I sure as hell know I wasn’t told be some school teacher. When I learned it there was no Bible in the teacher’s hand, he/she didn’t point to a statue of the Blessed Mother in the corner and detail the birth of Christ… it was by no means a lesson in religion. It was an oath of loyalty to one’s country that just happened to use “God” as a unifying factor.<br>
<br>
My only exposure to religion at that age was via my Grandmother, a Catholic. Had my Grandmother been a Hare Krishna I’m sure I would have interpreted “…one nation under God” to mean “…one nation under Krishna”. Yep, I'm clever like that.<br>
<br>
<font color=fff00>Secondly, personally I wouldn't be keen on saying it if I lived in the states, since I'm an agnostic. However, for deeply religious people of other beliefs (moslems, for example), I bet it'd be deeply disturbing to have to say that every day.</font><br>
<br>
If I lived in some of those Middle Eastern countries, I would find it deeply disturbing that I couldn’t kick back with a Playboy or some other form of pr0n anytime I wanted to. But I would also understand that those laws were embedded into their culture before my grandparents were born. If I couldn’t deal with it I would move, not attempt to change the country to fit my beliefs.<br>
<br>
And who says they “had” to say it? If you don’t want to do something, then don’t... what a profound concept! <p><b>Vendrix</b><br>
